mt_raw:
With assistance from the Secretary for Financial Services and the Treasury, the Financial Secretary is accountable to the public for maintaining the stability and soundness of Hong Kong’s financial system and for implementing policies to uphold Hong Kong’s status as an international financial center. Key responsibilities of the Financial Management Specialist include:
- Promoting overall stability and effective operation of the banking system;
- Collaborating with other relevant bodies and organizations to develop debt markets;
- Handling issuance and circulation of legal tender notes and coins;
- Developing and overseeing payment, clearing, and settlement systems, and operating these systems when appropriate, to enhance the safety and efficiency of financial infrastructure; and
- Working with other relevant bodies and organizations to foster confidence in Hong Kong’s monetary and financial systems, and implementing market development measures to help strengthen Hong Kong’s financial industry’s global competitiveness.

The monetary base (Table 1) includes:
- Certificates of Indebtedness (fully backing banknotes issued by three note-issuing banks);
- Circulating banknotes and coins issued by the government;
- The total balance of the settlement accounts at the Exchange Fund and the HKMA (the total balance); and
- The foreign exchange fund notes and bonds issued by the HKMA on behalf of the government.

The Exchange Fund Advisory Committee sets the following investment objectives for the Exchange Fund:
(i) to safeguard capital;
(ii) to ensure that the overall monetary base is fully supported at all times by highly liquid USD assets;
(iii) to ensure sufficient liquidity is maintained to support monetary and financial stability; and
(iv) to strive for investment returns in line with the above (i) to (iii), thus safeguarding the long-term purchasing power of the Exchange Fund.

The scope of the Risk Committee includes:
- Identifying potential risks and threats facing the HKMA and formulating strategies to mitigate their impact;
- Reviewing existing risk management systems across departments, identifying vulnerabilities and major risks, and ensuring appropriate measures are in place;
- Standardizing risk assessment criteria and methods, and prioritizing resource allocation based on identified risks; and
- Encouraging and strengthening a risk-aware culture within the HKMA, promoting appropriate delegation and supervision.

The audit procedures relating to the valuation of financial assets and liabilities at fair value included:
- Understanding the valuation procedures for different categories of financial assets and liabilities, including related monitoring controls;
- Evaluating and testing the controls, including the relevant application controls on computer systems;
- Obtaining and verifying valuation reports for financial assets and liabilities, and confirming that the fair values are based on the valuation reports;
- Verifying prices against independent sources when market quotations are used;
- When valuation uses observable market data, evaluating whether the valuation techniques are appropriate, and whether the assumptions made are reasonable, and verifying the inputs from independent sources; and
- When valuation uses non-observable inputs, assessing whether the valuation techniques are appropriate, and whether the assumptions and inputs used are reasonable.

During the audit in accordance with Hong Kong Standards on Auditing, I exercise professional judgment and maintain professional skepticism. I also:
- Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement in the financial statements due to fraud or error, design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks, and gather sufficient and appropriate audit evidence to provide a basis for my opinion. Because fraud may involve collusion, falsification, deliberate omission, false representations, or override of internal controls, the risk of not detecting a material misstatement due to fraud is higher than for error;
- Understand the internal controls related to the audit in order to design appropriate audit procedures. However, this does not constitute an opinion on the effectiveness of the Group’s internal controls;
- Evaluate whether the accounting policies adopted by the Financial Secretary are appropriate, and whether the accounting estimates and related disclosures are reasonable;
- Conclude on whether the use of the going concern basis of accounting is appropriate, and, based on the audit evidence obtained, whether there are material uncertainties related to events or conditions that may cast significant doubt on the Group’s ability to continue as a going concern. If I conclude that such uncertainties exist, I am required to draw attention in my auditor’s report to the related disclosures in the financial statements. If the disclosures are inadequate, I must draw the auditor’s attention to that fact. My conclusions are based on the audit evidence obtained up to the date of my auditor’s report. However, future events or conditions may cause the Group to cease to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure, and content of the financial statements, including the disclosures; and
- Obtain sufficient appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of the entities or business activities within the Group to express an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for directing, supervising, and performing the group audit. I bear all of the responsibility for my audit opinion.
